# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: power-integrity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] In electronics, a **decoupling capacitor** is a capacitor used to decouple (i.e. prevent electrical energy from transferring to) one part of a circuit from another.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Noise caused by other circuit elements is shunted through the capacitor, reducing its effect on the rest of the circuit.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] For higher frequencies, an alternative name is **bypass capacitor** as it is used to bypass the power supply or other high-impedance component of a circuit.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Active devices of an electronic system (e.g. transistors, integrated circuits, vacuum tubes) are connected to their power supplies through conductors with finite resistance and inductance.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] If the current drawn by an active device changes, the voltage drop from the power supply to the device will also change due to these impedances.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] A decoupling capacitor provides a bypass path for transient currents, instead of flowing through the common impedance.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] The decoupling capacitor works as the device’s local energy storage.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] The capacitor is placed between the power line and the ground to the circuit the current is to be provided.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] a voltage drop between a power line and the ground results in a current drawn out from the capacitor to the circuit.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] When capacitance C is large enough, sufficient current is supplied to maintain an acceptable range of voltage drop.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] The capacitor stores a small amount of energy that can compensate for the voltage drop in the power supply conductors to the capacitor.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] To reduce undesired parasitic equivalent series inductance, small and large capacitors are often placed in parallel, adjacent to individual integrated circuits (see § Placement).
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] In digital circuits, decoupling capacitors also help prevent radiation of electromagnetic interference from relatively long circuit traces due to rapidly changing power supply currents.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Decoupling capacitors alone may not suffice in such cases as a high-power amplifier stage with a low-level pre-amplifier coupled to it.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Care must be taken in the layout of circuit conductors so that heavy current at one stage does not produce power supply voltage drops that affect other stages.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] This may require re-routing printed circuit board traces to segregate circuits, or the use of a ground plane to improve the stability of power supply.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] A bypass capacitor is often used to decouple a subcircuit from AC signals or voltage spikes on a power supply or other line.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] A bypass capacitor can shunt energy from those signals, or transients, past the subcircuit to be decoupled, right to the return path.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] For a power supply line, a bypass capacitor from the supply voltage line to the power supply return (neutral) would be used.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] High frequencies and transient currents can flow through a capacitor to circuit ground instead of to the harder path of the decoupled circuit, but DC cannot go through the capacitor and continues to the decoupled circuit.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Another kind of decoupling is stopping a portion of a circuit from being affected by switching that occurs in another portion of the circuit.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Switching in subcircuit A may cause fluctuations in the power supply or other electrical lines, but you do not want subcircuit B, which has nothing to do with that switching, to be affected.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] A decoupling capacitor can decouple subcircuits A and B so that B doesn't see any effects of the switching.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] In a subcircuit, switching will change the load current drawn from the source.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Typical power supply lines show inherent inductance, which results in a slower response to changes in current.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] The supply voltage will drop across these parasitic inductances for as long as the switching event occurs.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] This transient voltage drop would be seen by other loads as well if the inductance between two loads is much lower compared to the inductance between the loads and the output of the power supply.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] To decouple other subcircuits from the effect of the sudden current demand, a decoupling capacitor can be placed in parallel with the subcircuit, across its supply voltage lines.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] When switching occurs in the subcircuit, the capacitor supplies the transient current.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Ideally, by the time the capacitor runs out of charge, the switching event has finished, so that the load can draw full current at normal voltage from the power supply and the capacitor can recharge.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] The best way to reduce switching noise is to design a PCB as a giant capacitor by sandwiching the power and ground planes across a dielectric material.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Sometimes parallel combinations of capacitors are used to improve response.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] This is because real capacitors have parasitic inductance, which causes the impedance to deviate from that of an ideal capacitor at higher frequencies.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Transient load decoupling as described above is needed when there is a large load that gets switched quickly.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] The parasitic inductance in every (decoupling) capacitor may limit the suitable capacity and influence the appropriate type if switching occurs very fast.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Logic circuits tend to do sudden switching (an ideal logic circuit would switch from low voltage to high voltage instantaneously, with no middle voltage ever observable).
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] So logic circuit boards often have a decoupling capacitor close to each logic IC connected from each power supply connection to a nearby ground.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] These capacitors decouple every IC from every other IC in terms of supply voltage dips.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] These capacitors are often placed at each power source as well as at each analog component in order to ensure that the supplies are as steady as possible.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Otherwise, an analog component with a poor power supply rejection ratio (PSRR) will copy fluctuations in the power supply onto its output.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] In these applications, the decoupling capacitors are often called *bypass capacitors* to indicate that they provide an alternate path for high-frequency signals that would otherwise cause the normally steady supply voltage to change.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Those components that require quick injections of current can *bypass* the power supply by receiving the current from the nearby capacitor.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Hence, the slower power supply connection is used to charge these capacitors, and the capacitors actually provide large quantities of high-availability current.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] A transient load decoupling capacitor is placed as close as possible to the device causing the transient.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] This minimizes the amount of line inductance and series resistance between the decoupling capacitor and the device.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] The longer the conductor between the capacitor and the device, the more inductance is present.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] Since capacitors differ in their high-frequency characteristics, decoupling commonly involves the use of a combination of capacitors.
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] For example in logic circuits, a common arrangement is ~100 nF ceramic per logic IC (multiple ones for complex ICs), combined with electrolytic or tantalum capacitor(s).
[src:power-integrity/decoupling-capacitor] These photos show old printed circuit boards with through-hole capacitors, where as modern boards typically have tiny surface-mount capacitors.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] In electronic engineering, **ground bounce** is a phenomenon associated with transistor switching where the gate voltage can appear to be less than the local ground potential, causing the unstable operation of a logic gate.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] Ground bounce is usually seen on high density VLSI where insufficient precautions have been taken to supply a logic gate with a sufficiently low impedance connection to ground (or sufficiently high bypass capacitance).
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] Relative to this local ground, the base voltage can go negative, thus shutting off the transistor.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] As the excess local charge dissipates, the transistor turns back on, possibly causing a repeat of the phenomenon, sometimes up to a half-dozen bounces.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] Ground bounce is one of the leading causes of "hung" or metastable gates in modern digital circuit design.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] This happens because the ground bounce puts the input of a flip flop effectively at voltage level that is neither a one nor a zero at clock time, or causes untoward effects in the clock itself.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] A similar voltage sag phenomenon may be seen on the collector side, called **supply voltage sag** (or ***V*CC sag**), where VCC is pulled unnaturally low.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] As a whole, ground bounce is a major issue in nanometer range technologies in VLSI.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] Ground bounce can also occur when the circuit board has poorly designed ground paths.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] Improper ground or VCC can lead to local variations in the ground level between various components.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] This is most commonly seen in circuit boards that have ground and VCC paths on the surfaces of the board.
[src:power-integrity/ground-bounce] Ground bounce may be reduced by placing a 10 to 30 ohm resistor in series to each of the switching outputs to limit the current flow during the gate switch.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] PI engineering focuses on designing and evaluating power supply subsystems to prevent any degradation in system performance due to potential adverse effects from the power supplies.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] For instance, a noisy power supply can cause audible or visible disturbances or slow down data communication.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] PI engineering employs various methods to minimize or eliminate such noise.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The effectiveness of PI engineering is measured by the overall system performance, even though it specifically addresses power supply circuits.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] In other words, PI engineering identifies circuit blocks that are sensitive to power supply perturbations and requires careful attention.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] PI is essential for achieving successful signal integrity (SI) engineering, which deals with impedance matching among multiple elements.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] Like SI, PI also ensures proper connections between a power supply and a load device, which is often a concern for SI.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] This connection path is known as a power delivery network (PDN), and tuning the PDN path from the power source to load devices is referred to as PDN impedance design.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] In the Computer industry, the increasing power demands of Microprocessors necessitated dedicated decoupling capacitor designs for power supply buses on printed circuit boards.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] As a microprocessor transitions between idle and heavy computation states, it draws rapidly changing current from its power supply unit, often referred to as a voltage regulator module (VRM).
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] This can lead to potential over-voltage damage to the microprocessor.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] from a power bus, the instantaneous current supply comes from decoupling capacitors until the VRM begins supplying current.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] This causes a drop in power bus voltage (undershoot), potentially leading to digital data loss as the microprocessor's internal logic circuitry may fail to maintain digital high or low states.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The engineering efforts involved in designing these decoupling capacitors laid the foundation for PDN impedance design.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The current path from the power supply through the PCB and IC package to the die (consumer) is called the power distribution network.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] Its role is to transfer the power to the consumers with little DC voltage drop, and to allow little ripple induced by dynamic current at the consumer (switching current).
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The DC voltage drop occurs if there is too much resistance in the plane or power traces leading from the VRM (Voltage Regulator Module) to the consumer.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] This can be countered by raising the voltage on the VRM, or extending the "sense" point of the VRM to the consumer.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] Dynamic current occurs when the consumer switches its transistors, typically triggered by a clock signal.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] This dynamic current can be considerably larger than the static current (internal leakage) of the consumer.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] This fast change in current consumption can pull the voltage of the rail down, or cause it to spike, creating a voltage ripple.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] This change in current happens much faster than the VRM can react.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The switching current must therefore be handled by decoupling capacitors.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The noise or voltage ripple must be handled differently depending on the frequency of operation.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The highest frequencies must be handled on-die.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] This noise is decoupled by parasitic coupling on the die, and capacitive coupling between metal layers.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] Frequencies above 50–100 MHz must be handled on the package.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] Frequencies below 100 MHz are handled on the PCB by plane capacitance and using decoupling capacitors.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] Capacitors work on different frequencies depending on their type, capacitance and physical size.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] It is therefore necessary to utilize multiple capacitors of different sizes to ensure a low PDN impedance across the frequency range.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The physical size of the capacitors affect its parasitic inductance.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The parasitic inductance creates impedance spikes at certain frequencies.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] Physically smaller capacitors are therefore better.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The placement of the capacitors is of varying importance depending on its frequency of operation.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The smallest value capacitors should be as close as possible to the consumer to minimize the AC current loop area.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] Larger capacitors in the microfarad range can be placed more or less anywhere.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] The target impedance is the impedance at which the ripple created by the dynamic current of the specific consumer is within the specified range.
[src:power-integrity/power-integrity] In addition to the target impedance, it is important to know which frequencies it applies, and at which frequency the consumer package is responsible (this is specified in the datasheet of the specific consumer IC).
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] In telecommunications, **return loss** is a measure in relative terms of the power of the signal reflected by a discontinuity in a transmission line or optical fiber.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] This discontinuity can be caused by a mismatch between the termination or load connected to the line and the characteristic impedance of the line.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] where RL(dB) is the return loss in dB, *P*i is the incident power, and *P*r is the reflected power.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] Return loss is related to both standing wave ratio (SWR) and reflection coefficient (Γ).
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] Increasing return loss corresponds to lower SWR.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] Return loss is a measure of how well devices or lines are matched.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] A match is good if the return loss is high.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] A high return loss is desirable and results in a lower insertion loss.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] From a certain perspective "return loss" is a misnomer.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] The usual function of a transmission line is to convey power from a source to a load with minimal loss.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] If a transmission line is correctly matched to a load, the reflected power will be zero, no power will be lost due to reflection, and "return loss" will be infinite.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] Conversely if the line is terminated in an open circuit, the reflected power will be equal to the incident power; all of the incident power will be lost in the sense that none of it will be transferred to a load, and RL will be zero.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] Thus the numerical values of RL tend in the opposite sense to that expected of a "loss".
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] As defined above, RL will always be positive, since *P*r can never exceed *P*i.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] However, return loss has historically been expressed as a negative number, and this convention is still widely found in the literature.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] where RL′(dB) is the negative of RL(dB).
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] In practice, the sign ascribed to RL is largely immaterial.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] If a transmission line includes several discontinuities along its length, the total return loss will be the sum of the RLs caused by each discontinuity, and provided all RLs are given the same sign, no error or ambiguity will result.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] Whichever convention is used, it will always be understood that *P*r can never exceed *P*i.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] In metallic conductor systems, reflections of a signal traveling down a conductor can occur at a discontinuity or impedance mismatch.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] of the amplitude of the reflected wave *V*r to the amplitude of the incident wave *V*i is known as the reflection coefficient.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] Return loss is the negative of the magnitude of the reflection coefficient in dB.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] where the vertical bars indicate magnitude.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] Thus, a large positive return loss indicates that the reflected power is small relative to the incident power, which indicates good impedance match between transmission line and load.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] In optics (particularly in fiber optics) a loss that takes place at discontinuities of refractive index, especially at an air–glass interface such as a fiber endface.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] At those interfaces, a fraction of the optical signal is reflected back toward the source.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] This reflection phenomenon is also called "**Fresnel reflection loss**", or simply "**Fresnel loss**".
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] (where $P_{\text{r}}$ is the reflected power, and $P_{\text{i}}$ is the incident, or input, power) can cause the laser to stop transmitting correctly.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] The measurement of ORL is becoming more important in the characterization of optical networks as the use of wavelength-division multiplexing increases.
[src:power-integrity/return-loss] These systems use lasers that have a lower tolerance for ORL and introduce elements into the network that are located in close proximity to the laser.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Some of the **main issues** of concern for signal integrity are ringing, crosstalk, ground bounce, distortion, signal loss, and power supply noise.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Signal integrity primarily involves the electrical performance of the wires and other packaging structures used to move signals about within an electronic product.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Such performance is a matter of basic physics and as such has remained relatively unchanged since the inception of electronic signaling.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The first transatlantic telegraph cable suffered from severe signal integrity problems, and analysis of the problems yielded many of the mathematical tools still used today to analyze signal integrity problems, such as the telegrapher's equations.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Products as old as the Western Electric crossbar telephone exchange (circa 1940), based on the wire-spring relay, suffered almost all the effects seen today - the ringing, crosstalk, ground bounce, and power supply noise that plague modern digital products.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] On printed circuit boards, signal integrity became a serious concern when the transition (rise and fall) times of signals started to become comparable to the propagation time across the board.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Very roughly speaking, this typically happens when system speeds exceed a few tens of MHz.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] At first, only a few of the most important, or highest speed, signals needed detailed analysis or design.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] As speeds increased, a larger and larger fraction of signals needed SI analysis and design practices.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In modern (> 100 MHz) circuit designs, essentially all signals must be designed with SI in mind.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] For ICs, SI analysis became necessary as an effect of reduced design rules.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In the early days of the modern VLSI era, digital chip circuit design and layout were manual processes.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] However, scaling trends (see Moore's law) brought electrical effects back to the forefront in recent technology nodes.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] With scaling of technology below 0.25 μm, the wire delays have become comparable or even greater than the gate delays.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] As a result, the wire delays needed to be considered to achieve timing closure.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In nanometer technologies at 0.13 μm and below, unintended interactions between signals (e.g. crosstalk) became an important consideration for digital design.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] At these technology nodes, the performance and correctness of a design cannot be assured without considering noise effects.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Most of this article is about SI in relation to modern electronic technology - notably the use integrated circuits and printed circuit board technology.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Nevertheless, the principles of SI are not exclusive to the signalling technology used.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] SI existed long before the advent of either technology, and will do so as long as electronic communications persist.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The cost of these failures is very high, and includes photomask costs, engineering costs and opportunity cost due to delayed product introduction.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Therefore, electronic design automation (EDA) tools have been developed to analyze, prevent, and correct these problems.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In integrated circuits, or ICs, the main cause of signal integrity problems is crosstalk.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In CMOS technologies, this is primarily due to coupling capacitance, but in general it may be caused by mutual inductance, substrate coupling, non-ideal gate operation, and other sources.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The fixes normally involve changing the sizes of drivers and/or spacing of wires.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In analog circuits, designers are also concerned with noise that arise from physical sources, such as thermal noise, flicker noise, and shot noise.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] These noise sources on the one hand present a lower limit to the smallest signal that can be amplified, and on the other, define an upper limit to the useful amplification.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In digital ICs, noise in a signal of interest arises primarily from coupling effects from switching of other signals.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Increasing interconnect density has led to each wire having neighbors that are physically closer together, leading to increased crosstalk between neighboring nets.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] These effects have increased the interactions between signals and decreased the noise immunity of digital CMOS circuits.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] This has led to noise being a significant problem for digital ICs that must be considered by every digital chip designer prior to tape-out.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Modern signal integrity tools for IC design perform all these steps automatically, producing reports that give a design a clean bill of health, or a list of problems that must be fixed.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] However, such tools generally are not applied across an entire IC, but only selected signals of interest.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Once a problem is found, it must be fixed.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Each of these fixes may possibly cause other problems.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] This type of issue must be addressed as part of design flows and design closure.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Re-analysis after design changes is a prudent measure.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] On-die termination (ODT) or Digitally Controlled Impedance (DCI) is the technology where the termination resistor for impedance matching in transmission lines is located within a semiconductor chip, instead of a separate, discrete device mounted on a circuit board.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The closeness of the termination from the receiver shorten the stub between the two, thus improving the overall signal integrity.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] For wired connections, it is important to compare the interconnect flight time to the bit period to decide whether an impedance matched or unmatched connection is needed.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The channel flight time (delay) of the interconnect is roughly 1 ns per 15 cm (6 in) of FR-4 stripline (the propagation velocity depends on the dielectric and the geometry).
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Reflections of previous pulses at impedance mismatches die down after a few bounces up and down the line (i.e. on the order of the flight time).
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] At low bit rates, the echoes die down on their own, and by midpulse, they are not a concern.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Impedance matching is neither necessary nor desirable.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] There are many circuit board types other than FR-4, but usually they are more costly to manufacture.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The gentle trend to higher bit rates accelerated dramatically in 2004, with the introduction by Intel of the PCI-Express standard.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Examples of mitigation techniques for these impairments are a redesign of the via geometry to ensure an impedance match, use of differential signaling, and preemphasis filtering, respectively.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] At these new multigigabit/s bit rates, the bit period is shorter than the flight time; echoes of previous pulses can arrive at the receiver on top of the main pulse and corrupt it.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In communication engineering this is called intersymbol interference (ISI).
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In signal integrity engineering it is usually called eye closure (a reference to the clutter in the center of a type of oscilloscope trace called an eye diagram).
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] When the bit period is shorter than the flight time, elimination of reflections using classic microwave techniques like matching the electrical impedance of the transmitter to the interconnect, the sections of interconnect to each other, and the interconnect to the receiver, is crucial.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Termination with a source or load is a synonym for matching at the two ends.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The interconnect impedance that can be selected is constrained by the impedance of free space (~377 Ω), a geometric form factor and by the square root of the relative dielectric constant of the stripline filler (typically FR-4, with a relative dielectric constant of ~4).
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Together, these properties determine the trace's characteristic impedance.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] 50 Ω is a convenient choice for single-end lines, and 100 ohm for differential.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] As a consequence of the low impedance required by matching, PCB signal traces carry much more current than their on-chip counterparts.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] This larger current induces crosstalk primarily in a magnetic or inductive mode as opposed to a capacitive mode.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] To combat this crosstalk, digital PCB designers must remain acutely aware of not only the intended signal path for every signal, but also the path of returning signal current for every signal.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The signal itself and its returning signal current path are equally capable of generating inductive crosstalk.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Differential trace pairs help to reduce these effects.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] A third difference between on-chip and chip-to-chip connection involves the cross-sectional size of the signal conductor, namely that PCB conductors are much larger (typically 100 μm or more in width).
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Thus, PCB traces have a small series resistance (typically 0.1 Ω/cm) at DC.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The high frequency component of the pulse is however attenuated by additional resistance due to the skin effect and dielectric loss tangent associated with the PCB material.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The main challenge often depends on whether the project is a cost-driven consumer application or a performance-driven infrastructure application.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] They tend to require extensive post-layout verification (using an EM simulator) and pre-layout design optimization (using SPICE and a channel simulator), respectively.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] The noise levels on a trace/network is highly dependent on the routing topology selected.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] In a point-to-point topology, the signal is routed from the transmitter directly to the receiver (this is applied in PCIe, RapidIO, Gigabit Ethernet, DDR2/DDR3/DDR4 DQ/DQS etc.).
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] A point-to-point topology has the least SI-problems since there is no large impedance matches being introduced by line T's (a two-way split of a trace).
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] For interfaces where multiple packages are receiving from the same line, (for example with a backplane configuration), the line must be split at some point to service all receivers.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Some stubs and impedance mismatches are deemed to occur.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Multipackage interfaces include BLVDS, DDR2/DDR3/DDR4 C/A bank, RS485 and CAN Bus.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] There are two main multipackage topologies: Tree and fly-by.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] There are special purpose EDA tools that help the engineer perform all these steps on each signal in a design, pointing out problems or verifying the design is ready for manufacture.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Signal Integrity (SI) in PCB design refers to the quality of electrical signals as they travel through traces, vias, and components on a printed circuit board.
[src:power-integrity/signal-integrity] Ensuring good signal integrity is critical for high-speed and high-frequency designs, as poor signal quality can lead to data errors, signal distortion, and system malfunction.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] On personal computer (PC) systems, the VRM is typically made up of power MOSFET devices.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] Most voltage regulator module implementations are soldered onto the motherboard.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] A voltage regulator integrated on-package or on-die is usually referred to as *fully integrated voltage regulator* (*FIVR*) or simply an *integrated voltage regulator* (*IVR*).
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] Most modern CPUs require less than 1.5 V, as CPU designers tend to use lower CPU core voltages; lower voltages help in reducing CPU power dissipation, which is often specified through thermal design power (TDP) that serves as the nominal value for designing CPU cooling systems.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] Some voltage regulators provide a fixed supply voltage to the processor, but most of them sense the required supply voltage from the processor, essentially acting as a continuously-variable adjustable regulator.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] In particular, VRMs that are soldered to the motherboard are supposed to do the sensing, according to the Intel specification.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] Modern video cards also use a VRM due to higher power and current requirements.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] These VRMs may generate a significant amount of heat and require heat sinks separate from the GPU.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] The correct supply voltage and current is communicated by the microprocessor to the VRM at startup via a number of bits called *VID* (voltage identification definition).
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] In particular, the VRM initially provides a standard supply voltage to the VID logic, which is the part of the processor whose only aim is to then send the VID to the VRM.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] When the VRM has received the VID identifying the required supply voltage, it starts acting as a voltage regulator, providing the required constant voltage and current supply to the processor.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] Instead of having a power supply unit generate some fixed voltage, the CPU uses a small set of digital signals, the VID lines, to instruct an on-board power converter of the desired voltage level.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] The switch-mode buck converter then adjusts its output accordingly.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] The flexibility so obtained makes it possible to use the same power supply unit for CPUs with different nominal supply voltages and to reduce power consumption during idle periods by lowering the supply voltage.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] For example, a unit with 5-bit VID would output one of at most 32 (25) distinct output voltages.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] These voltages are usually (but not always) evenly spaced within a given range.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] Some of the code words may be reserved for special functions such as shutting down the unit, hence a 5-bit VID unit may have fewer than 32 output voltage levels.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] How the numerical codes map to supply voltages is typically specified in tables provided by component manufacturers.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] Since 2008 VID comes in 5-, 6- and 8-bit varieties and is mostly applied to power modules outputting between 0.5 V and 3.5 V.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] The VRMs are essential for overclocking.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] The quality of a VRM directly impacts the motherboard’s overclocking potential.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] The same overclocked processor can exhibit noticeable performance differences when paired with different VRMs.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] The reason for this is that a steady power supply is needed for successful overclocking.
[src:power-integrity/voltage-regulator-module] When a chip is pushed past its factory settings, that increases the power draw, so the VRM needs to match its output accordingly.
